OCCE Fact Sheet

HVAC and Surface Temperature

Literature has found associations between exposure to extreme heat with greater risks of cardiovascular mortality. Extreme heat is also a risk factor associated with hospitalization for cardiovascular diseases. In Miami-Dade county, alongside poor socioeconomic variables (age of home and household income) low rates of ownership of air conditioners (AC) and extreme surface temperatures present real danger to disadvantaged neighborhoods.

The bivariate map displayed illustrates potential dangers for individuals living in the Mimai-Dade area. Areas with both high mean surface temperatures and low ownership of AC are shaded dark blue. Areas with large populations of extreme concern, including Country Club, Hialeah,and Miami Gardens, have the oldest average age of homes and are some of the poorest places in Miami-Dade.
